    "# Research Notebook: Empirical Analysis of Trading Signals\n",
    "\n",
    "## Purpose\n",
    "\n",
    "The purpose of this research notebook is to provide empirical support for the three trading signals used in the assessment notebook. The notebook explains the economic idea behind each signal, tests different parameter choices, and evaluates whether the selected parameters remain plausible outside the calibration period.\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal is to show that the final trading signals are not chosen randomly. Instead, they are based on systematic in-sample testing, out-of-sample validation, performance statistics and graphical analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Structure of the Research Notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "| Section | Content | Purpose |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| 0 | Setup and Data | Downloads adjusted close prices and defines the in-sample and out-of-sample periods. |\n",
    "| 1 | Signal 1: Time-Series Momentum | Explains and tests a momentum signal based on past returns. |\n",
    "| 2 | Signal 2: Trading-Range Breakout | Explains and tests a breakout signal based on recent price highs. |\n",
    "| 3 | Signal 3: Volatility-Adjusted Momentum | Explains and tests a momentum signal adjusted for recent volatility. |\n",
    "| 4 | Comparison and Robustness | Compares the final signals against buy-and-hold benchmarks. |\n",
    "| 5 | Final Parameter Choice | Summarizes the selected parameters used in the assessment notebook. |"
   ]
