    "## Section 1: Signal 1 — Time-Series Momentum\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.1 Economic Motivation and Literature\n",
    "\n",
    "The first signal is a time-series momentum signal. It is based on the idea that an asset's own past return can contain information about its future return. If a stock has performed positively over a previous lookback period, the strategy interprets this as evidence of an upward trend and invests in the stock.\n",
    "\n",
    "This idea is closely related to the time-series momentum literature. Moskowitz, Ooi and Pedersen (2012) show that an asset's own past return can predict future returns across different asset classes. In this notebook, the idea is adapted into a long-only equity trading signal.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.2 Signal Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "R_{t,n} = \\frac{P_t}{P_{t-n}} - 1\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Signal_t =\n",
    "\\begin{cases}\n",
    "1, & \\text{if } R_{t,n} > 0 \\\\\n",
    "0, & \\text{otherwise}\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where \\(P_t\\) is the adjusted closing price at time \\(t\\), \\(P_{t-n}\\) is the adjusted closing price \\(n\\) trading days before, and \\(n\\) is the lookback window.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.3 Parameter Search\n",
    "\n",
    "The main parameter of this signal is the lookback window \\(n\\). Shorter windows react more quickly to recent price changes, while longer windows capture more persistent trends. The parameter search therefore tests several lookback windows that represent different investment horizons.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Parameter | Meaning | Values Tested |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| `lookback_window` | Number of trading days used to calculate past return | 60, 90, 120, 180, 252 |\n",
    "\n",
    "These values roughly represent three months, four months, six months, nine months and one trading year."
   ]
