    "## Section 2: Signal 2 — Trading-Range Breakout\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.1 Economic Motivation and Literature\n",
    "\n",
    "The second signal is a trading-range breakout signal. It is based on the idea that a price breaking above a recent high can indicate strong buying pressure and the beginning or continuation of an upward trend.\n",
    "\n",
    "In technical trading literature, breakout rules are often interpreted as signals that resistance levels have been overcome. Brock, Lakonishok and LeBaron (1992) study simple technical trading rules, including trading-range breakouts, and find evidence that such rules can contain information about future returns.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.2 Signal Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "The recent high is defined as the maximum adjusted closing price over the previous \\(n\\) trading days:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_{t,n} = \\max(P_{t-n}, ..., P_{t-1})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The trading signal is then defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "Signal_t =\n",
    "\\begin{cases}\n",
    "1, & \\text{if } P_t > H_{t,n} \\\\\n",
    "0, & \\text{otherwise}\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where \\(P_t\\) is the adjusted closing price at time \\(t\\), and \\(H_{t,n}\\) is the highest price over the previous \\(n\\) trading days.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.3 Parameter Search\n",
    "\n",
    "The main parameter of this signal is the breakout window \\(n\\). A shorter window reacts more quickly to price movements, while a longer window requires the stock to break above a more meaningful historical high.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Parameter | Meaning | Values Tested |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| `breakout_window` | Number of previous trading days used to define the recent high | 20, 50, 100, 150, 252 |\n",
    "\n",
    "These values represent short-term, medium-term and approximately one-year breakout horizons."
   ]
